Automated Testing and TDD — Explained Simply
1. What is Automated Testing?

Automated testing is the process of using software tools and scripts to automatically execute test cases, compare actual results with expected results, and report whether the software passes or fails.

Manual Testing

A tester manually performs actions:

Open application
Enter username
Enter password
Click Login
Check whether login succeeds
Automated Testing

A program performs the same steps automatically:

testLogin()
{
    openApplication();
    enterUsername("user1");
    enterPassword("1234");
    clickLogin();
    assert(loginSuccessful == true);
}

So, instead of a human repeating the same test every time, a testing tool executes it automatically.

2. Benefits of Automated Testing
1. Saves Time

Automated tests can execute hundreds or thousands of test cases quickly.

2. Reduces Human Errors

A person may accidentally enter the wrong input or miss a step. Automated scripts perform the same steps consistently.

3. Tests Can Be Repeated Easily

The same tests can be run after every code change.

4. Faster Feedback

Developers can immediately know whether a new change has broken existing functionality.

5. Supports Regression Testing

Regression testing means checking that new changes have not broken old functionality.

Example:

Version 1: Login works
Version 2: Add payment feature

After adding payment, automated tests can quickly check:

Login still works?
Registration still works?
Search still works?
Payment works?
6. Better Software Quality

Automated testing helps find bugs early.

7. Useful in CI/CD

Automated tests can run automatically whenever developers push code to platforms such as GitHub or a build server.

Important: Automation does not completely replace manual testing. Exploratory testing, usability testing, and tests requiring human judgment may still need manual testers.

3. Types of Tests

Software testing can be divided into several levels.

A. Unit Testing

Tests the smallest individual part of a program, usually a method or function.

Example:

public int Add(int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
}

Unit test:

[Test]
public void Add_ReturnsCorrectSum()
{
    int result = Add(2, 3);

    Assert.That(result, Is.EqualTo(5));
}

Here, only the Add() method is being tested.

Characteristics
Very fast
Tests small pieces of code
Easy to run frequently
B. Integration Testing

Tests whether multiple components work correctly together.

Example:

Application
    ↓
Database
    ↓
Payment Service

An integration test may check whether:

Application → Database

works correctly.

C. System / End-to-End Testing

Tests the complete application from beginning to end.

Example of an e-commerce test:

Open website
    ↓
Login
    ↓
Search product
    ↓
Add product to cart
    ↓
Make payment
    ↓
Receive order confirmation

This tests the complete system.

D. Acceptance Testing

Checks whether the software satisfies the requirements of the customer or user.

Example:

Requirement:

A customer must be able to successfully purchase a product.

Acceptance test:

Given a logged-in customer
When the customer buys a product
Then the order should be successfully created
E. Regression Testing

Checks whether existing features still work after new changes are made.

Example:

Old Feature: Login
New Feature: Online Payment

After adding online payment, regression tests verify that login still works.

F. Performance Testing

Checks the performance of the system.

It may measure:

Response time
Number of users supported
Memory usage
CPU usage
System stability

Example:

Can the application handle 10,000 users simultaneously?
4. The Test Pyramid

The Test Pyramid is a strategy for deciding how many tests should be written at different levels.

It generally looks like this:

             /\
            /  \
           / E2E\
          /------\
         /        \
        /Integration\
       /------------\
      /              \
     /  Unit Tests    \
    /------------------\

The basic idea is:

Write many fast unit tests, fewer integration tests, and very few end-to-end tests.

Bottom: Unit Tests

You should have many unit tests.

1000 unit tests

Advantages:

Fast
Cheap
Easy to debug
Middle: Integration Tests

You should have fewer integration tests.

100 integration tests

They test the communication between components.

Example:

Application ↔ Database
Top: End-to-End Tests

You should have fewer end-to-end tests.

10 E2E tests

They test the entire application.

They are usually:

Slow
More expensive
More difficult to maintain
Simple Example

Imagine an online shopping application.

Test Type	Example	Number
Unit	Calculate total price	Many
Integration	Application connects to database	Some
E2E	Login → Cart → Payment → Order	Few

The Test Pyramid promotes a fast and reliable test suite.

